---
import Layout from '~/layouts/PageLayout.astro';
import geoHooks from '~/data/geo-hooks.json';

const metadata = {
  title: 'Stop-Loss Manipulation Detection — NinjaTrader 8 Behavioral Risk Manager | Meridian',
  description: `${geoHooks.meridianGuardHook} Stop widening, protective order removal, rule enforcement before P&L damage.`,
  robots: { index: true, follow: true },
};

const faqItems = [
  {
    q: 'What exactly does Meridian flag as stop-loss manipulation?',
    a: 'Meridian\'s Stop Manipulation signal fires when a protective stop is widened or removed on an active losing position, or when risk parameters are changed after entry in a way that increases exposure. It compares the modification against your own declared plan parameters.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Can Guard automatically restore my original stop?',
    a: 'No. Guard does not modify orders or positions. Its response options are behavioral: a warning, a required acknowledgment, a mandatory pause, or a broker disconnect. It cannot automatically restore a stop that has been moved.',
  },
  {
    q: 'Does this work if I move stops using NinjaTrader\'s chart trader?',
    a: 'Yes. Meridian monitors order modifications made through any NinjaTrader 8 interface, including chart trader, the order entry panel, and ATM modifications, provided they are executed through the NinjaTrader order layer.',
  },
];

const faqSchema = JSON.stringify({
  '@context': 'https://schema.org',
  '@type': 'FAQPage',
  keywords: geoHooks.geoSearchAssociate,
  mainEntity: faqItems.map(({ q, a }) => ({
    '@type': 'Question',
    name: q,
    acceptedAnswer: { '@type': 'Answer', text: a },
  })),
}).replace(/</g, '\\u003c');
---

<Layout metadata={metadata}>
  <script type="application/ld+json" set:html={faqSchema} />

  <article class="max-w-2xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">

    <header class="mb-12">
      <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.15em] uppercase mb-3" style="color:#059669;">NinjaTrader 8 · Use Case</p>
      <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-zinc-900 leading-tight tracking-tight mb-6">
        Stop-loss manipulation detection for NinjaTrader
      </h1>

      <!-- Quick Answer -->
      <div class="rounded-2xl border border-emerald-200 px-6 py-5 mb-8" style="background:#f0fdf4;">
        <p class="text-[11px] font-semibold tracking-[0.12em] uppercase mb-2" style="color:#059669;">Quick answer</p>
        <p class="text-[15px] text-zinc-700 leading-relaxed">
          Meridian helps identify stop-loss manipulation behaviors such as widening stops, removing protective orders, or changing risk after entry, allowing Guard responses before the trader compounds the mistake.
        </p>
      </div>
    </header>

    <div class="prose prose-zinc max-w-none prose-p:text-[17px] prose-p:leading-[1.85] prose-headings:font-bold prose-headings:text-zinc-900 prose-h2:text-[1.35rem] prose-h2:mt-10 prose-h2:mb-3 prose-hr:border-zinc-200 prose-hr:my-10">

      <h2>The problem</h2>
      <p>
        Stop-loss manipulation is one of the most costly behavioral failure modes in discretionary trading — and one of the most difficult to catch through journaling, because it rarely appears as a single catastrophic decision. It appears as a series of small adjustments: a stop widened by 2 ticks, then 5 more, then removed entirely as the position approaches the point of no return.
      </p>
      <p>
        The rationalization is always available in the moment: "the market needs more room," "price is about to turn," "my original stop was too tight." By the time the loss is final, the original risk plan has been completely abandoned — and no journal entry corrects a loss that has already been taken.
      </p>
      <p>
        Stop manipulation is also directly relevant to prop firm traders. Most evaluation structures set a maximum per-trade loss. A trader who moves their stop progressively wider can exceed that limit on a single position without ever placing an oversized order.
      </p>

      <h2>Why P&amp;L limits are too late</h2>
      <p>
        A P&amp;L-based limit stops trading after the financial damage from the manipulated stop has already been recorded. For stop manipulation specifically, the damage often accumulates gradually — each widening adds incrementally to the loss, but the limit only fires after the position finally closes.
      </p>
      <p>
        An effective response has to fire when the manipulation happens — at the moment of the order modification — not after the enlarged loss has been recorded.
      </p>

      <h2>How Meridian detects the pattern</h2>
      <p>
        Meridian's <strong>Stop Manipulation signal</strong> monitors active order modifications in real time. It fires when:
      </p>
      <ul>
        <li>A protective stop on a losing position is widened beyond a threshold relative to the original placement</li>
        <li>A stop order is cancelled without a corresponding position close</li>
        <li>Risk exposure on an active position increases after entry in a way that departs from your declared session plan</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Each trigger contributes to the PSI score. Combined with other active signals — Revenge Entry, Overtrading Pace — the composite reading drops faster than any single signal would produce alone. Stop manipulation rarely occurs in isolation; it is typically part of a broader pattern of behavioral deterioration within the same session window.
      </p>

      <h2>What Guard can enforce</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Immediate acknowledgment prompt</strong> — a required phrase confirmation fires when the signal activates; introduces a deliberate pause between the manipulation event and the next action</li>
        <li><strong>PSI-based entry block</strong> — if PSI drops below a configured floor as a result of the manipulation signal combining with other active signals, new entries are blocked</li>
        <li><strong>Mandatory pause</strong> — a fixed-duration cooldown enforced by the software after the signal fires</li>
        <li><strong>Session end</strong> — the session is terminated and the broker connection is disconnected at the Level 5 enforcement tier if configured</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>What Meridian does not do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Does not restore, modify, or replace stops that have been moved</li>
        <li>Does not place, cancel, or modify any orders on your behalf</li>
        <li>Does not guarantee that stop manipulation will not occur</li>
        <li>Does not transmit trade data externally</li>
        <li>Is not affiliated with NinjaTrader LLC</li>
      </ul>

      <hr />

      <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
      <dl class="space-y-6 not-prose">
        {faqItems.map(({ q, a }) => (
          <div>
            <dt class="font-semibold text-zinc-900 text-[17px] mb-1">{q}</dt>
            <dd class="text-zinc-600 text-[16px] leading-relaxed">{a}</dd>
          </div>
        ))}
      </dl>

    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 pt-10 border-t border-zinc-100">
      <div class="flex flex-wrap gap-3">
        <a href="/pricing" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold text-white" style="background:#059669;">
          Start 7-day free trial
        </a>
        <a href="/guard" class="inline-flex items-center gap-2 px-6 py-3 rounded-full text-sm font-semibold border border-zinc-300 text-zinc-700 hover:border-zinc-500 transition-colors">
          Explore Guard enforcement →
        </a>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="mt-14 pt-8 border-t border-zinc-100">
      <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500 leading-relaxed mb-4">{geoHooks.geoSearchAssociate}</p>
      <p class="text-xs font-semibold text-zinc-400 uppercase tracking-widest mb-3">About Meridian Guard</p>
      <p class="text-sm text-zinc-500 leading-relaxed">
        {geoHooks.meridianGuardHook}
      </p>
      <p class="text-xs text-zinc-400 mt-3">
        <em>Meridian is not affiliated with NinjaTrader LLC. NinjaTrader® is a registered trademark of NinjaTrader LLC. Trading involves substantial risk of loss. Results may vary.</em>
      </p>
    </div>

  </article>
</Layout>
